How did I start formulating?
Hi guys! I’m sure you’ve seen some of my stories with Hairfcker hair treatments. Now it’s time to share with you some details about it.
You know me as a hairdresser but I’ve been doing a lot of things in my life such as hair, photography, video, education, team building, salon interior design, sculpture and painting and now it’s the time for a new stage - creating our own hair products.
One of the core principles of Hairfucker is DIY. It means that if you are not happy with anything - you can do it better yourself and adapt to your own needs. That’s why the Hairfucker model is difficult to copy - as a collective of creative specialists we are the living being and we are always transforming, trying to do different things that are connected to the hair industry.
Shampoo, conditioner, deep treatment - these are the things that we use from “day one” in hairdressing. And each of you use it too. It’s not only a cleaning property - it is also a tool that helps to manage hair and give it a particular look. And we had to buy it from other brands that are always fighting for our attention
That’s why we always wanted to create our own. To be honest - it is a kind of a dream for many hairstylists who already opened salons and want to level up. But it is not an easy task. It always takes time, money, and energy. And of course the industry gives us plenty of opportunities to do it - from just labeling the existing product with your logo to turnkey solutions where you pay money and they do everything else. We discovered how it works many years ago visiting the largest expo all over the world (such as Cosmoprof Bologna, Hong Kong, Las Vegas) and found there so many things that we weren't happy with. And yes - we tried it a couple of times - that gave us the understanding - we need to create our own. This was the reason why I moved to the US. In the following posts I will share some more details about my way and the process. So keep in touch! #hairfucker #losangeleshairstylist #naturalhaircare

How did I start formulating. Part 2.
In 2021 we launched the first product that was manufactured for us and this product was really good. But it wasn’t exactly what we wanted.
The main idea was to create our own formula and make it customizable. Design and branding is also important - most of the products don’t look cool especially in the salon where everything is unique. And third thing - we want to make a sustainable product containing mostly natural ingredients - not every manufacturer does it.

 So this led us to the path - learn,make and use! Then again - learn,make and use, until you have a result that you're happy with. It takes a while and not every hairdresser can let himself spend nights after a full time job to do such a complex job. But I did. And  now I have something that works good and that came from my heart. It’s a lot of work to be done before we launch it but even now you can try it - and if you’re in LA you can try it with me)))

 In the following posts I will share some more details about my way and the process. So keep in touch!

Punk seeker. Social escape. Part 1.

Modern punk is a seeker. In a variety of styles and forms, when its native style was sold million times, sprinkled with sequins and glitter, put on the mezzanine and sold again, when glamour pulls on a punk outfit to become even more glamorous. Punk had to go again in search of self-identity, including external. When outrageousness, challenge and inadequate reaction began to be converted into currency of likes and the number of views on Tiktok, punk is again marginalized and leaves society in search of new or all the same old and eternal values that have not been spoiled by mass culture and consumer goods.

Punk-seeker is a pioneer of the self-decay of a culture that elevated the rebel to Olympus and rewarded him with diamonds, which in reality turned out to be just beautifully wrapped stones from the margins of capitalism. The bubble burst and the deception was exposed.

Punk-seeker is similar to his original ancestor of the 1970s in that he does not want to do anything and change. He just wants to live a life and like himself. And he considers everyone who tries to hide his inner emptiness behind a beautiful outer virtual wrapper as liars or lost souls.

Photos by @ylvaerevall 
#punkmanifesto #punkphilosophy #punk #seeker #archetypes #rebel #truelife #silentriot

Punk-seeker. Social escape. Part 2. Hair of a punk seeker is no longer a manifesto, now it is just a substance that can transform in any way, not limited to the need to terrorize a decent society. In the mind of a punk seeker, hair is generally an atavism, and it would be better if it did not exist at all. REALLY - why do we need these strange threads growing from the head, requiring constant care, but not carrying any useful function to the body. Wouldn't it be better to replace them with something more interesting, plastic and expressive. It may be worth abandoning hair altogether, replacing it with words, or a splash of anger, or music, for example. Imagine - a rebellious radical, on whose head a poem is written instead of hair, or exclamations of nihilism instead of a Mohawk.

There is no style and integrity of the images - they are replaced by intonation and a special manner of demonstrating their appearance - sometimes gloominess, discontent, confusion, coldness and outdatedness. Incoherent elements of clothing against the background of gloomy desert, disturbing landscapes seem to reveal abandoned and confused states of souls. There is no concept of appearance, as such, either - random elements of clothing, hairstyles and makeup, like uncontrolled flashes of thoughts in the head.  #morethannoise #marginalfashion #ineverwantnormalhairagain #punk #archetypes #rebel #riot #seekerarchetype #escaper #taboo #losangelespunk #losangeleshairstylist #losangelesbarber

August 3rd,  Los Angeles. Dm for details.

Dear  friends,  I want to invite you to our new art show INADEQUAT.  This will be the first exhibition I'm doing in California. You know me as a person who is obsessed with art and always  creating. Now, I  am ready to  share this art with people offline. This exhibition is not a usual thing, not just a collection of images on walls. It is a story of endless passion and creativity.  This exhibition is a result  of more than 100 collaborations of different artists and our team that was done during the last 15 years.  It consists  of hundreds or even thousands of images, and no  walls will be enough to hang so many pictures. That's why I  do it in a digital format. We turned all these images into psychedelic videos and will show them only once! I think that Instagram  isn't the right platform to share  art - to much of fast-food content of any genres at the same time doesn't give you  a possibility to feel the artistic message. That's why art, even digital art, should be exposed in museums, galleries, and live shows. Art needs a temple! And we are doing it in a small, cozy place just for a few hours - then it disappears like a dream in the morning.  Don't  miss it, and come to support underground creativity. 
When - August 3d,  7pm-10pm
Where - 6666 Santa Monica Blvd,  LA
Cost - pay as you  want.
In addition to video installations, there will be live performances at the event , thanks to my friends  who participates : 
@dnvnduelas , @ylvaerevall , @anianuinu , @irapopesage , @plazmonic , @hairfucker  and @newflowfactory 
Welcome and bring your friends!

Who does hair for a hairstylist? Typically, it's
another hairstylist. Less common is a stylist doing their own hair. In my case, I entrust my clients with this task. dynamic of trust is what makes the experience exciting, unpredictable, and immensely
interesting—especially when they take the shearsinto their own hands for the first time. In my quest to discover new shapes and ideas for hair, I've adopted an architectural mindset, merging the creativity of an architect with the precision of an engineer. Each hairstyle becomes a construction project, and my love for Brutalism, with its raw concrete monoliths, reflects in my work. In this video, I've transformed traditional hairdresser's tools into art sculptures, incorporating elements from everyday objects. These functional yet artistic pieces redefine the boundaries between hairstyling and architecture. What do you think, @dysonhair @wahlpro @ysparkusa @cocacola?

This year marks 20 years since I started working with hair. Once, I was a regular hairdresser, but then I thought, why can't a regular hairdresser become an artist? Something switched in me, and I began to seek new forms, experiment, investing my energy, time, and money into it. It's been 15 years since then, and I've never experienced what they call professional burnout. I've learned to see beauty in many unexpected things, draw ideas from the air, and, most importantly, inspire people. This led to the creation of a salon, then a school, and later art events that we organize – all of which significantly differed from what we saw in the hairdressing industry. I share this vision here on our YouTube channel and in my courses on creative vision. If you're here for the first time, subscribe; there's a lot of interesting content about hair and art.
